<!-- start template: ID 65, slashdot;journal;default -->

<div id="journalslashdot">
    
	<div class="journaldate">Sunday June 21, 2009</div>
	
	<div class="details">11:38 AM</div>
	<div class="title">
		<h3>Asking #perl about Modern Perl</h3>
	</div>
	<div class="adminoptions">
		[

			<a href="//use.perl.org/~masak/journal/39158">#39158</a>
		]
	</div>

	<div class="intro"><p>This is my first Perl 5 post ever. &#21704;&#21704; </p><p>

<code>
&lt;masak&gt; while I'm here, I'd like to talk about <a href="http://www.modernperlbooks.com/mt/2009/01/why-modern-perl.html" rel="nofollow">Modern Perl</a>.<br>
&lt;masak&gt; in y'all's opinion, what are the modules a Modern Perl 5 user should be aware of?<br>
&lt;masak&gt; I'm thinking of things like <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Moose/" rel="nofollow">Moose</a>, <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Scalar-List-Utils/" rel="nofollow">List::Util</a>, maybe <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Catalyst-Runtime/" rel="nofollow">Catalyst</a>...<br>
&lt;claes&gt; it all depends on what the task is<br>
&lt;lucs&gt; masak: <a href="http://dev.perl.org/perl5/news/2007/perl-5.10.0.html" rel="nofollow">5.10</a> in general maybe<br>
&lt;claes&gt; using <a href="http://perldoc.perl.org/warnings.html" rel="nofollow">warnings</a>, <a href="http://perldoc.perl.org/strict.html" rel="nofollow">strict</a> and perhaps <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/indirect/" rel="nofollow">indirect</a> pragmas<br>
&lt;masak&gt; I think things that we take for granted as good time-savers all qualify.<br>
&lt;masak&gt; so maybe stuff like <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Getopt-Long/" rel="nofollow">Getopt::Long</a> too.<br>
&lt;claes&gt; personaly I don't use Moose because I haven't had any use for it yet<br>
&lt;masak&gt; for me as a Perl 6 user, it's not that difficult to see the use for Moose.<br>
&lt;masak&gt; I saw a blog post recently that said that Moose even helped the blogger <a href="http://elliotlovesperl.com/2009/06/16/moose-as-documentation/" rel="nofollow">document things more succinctly</a>.<br>
&lt;masak&gt; that is, even when he wasn't using Moose, he was using habits gained from it to write better documentation.<br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Perl-Critic/" rel="nofollow">Perl::Critic</a>, definitely<br>
&lt;claes&gt; <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Devel-NYTProf/" rel="nofollow">Devel::NYTProf</a> <br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; some of the eventy things (<a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/AnyEvent/" rel="nofollow">AnyEvent</a>, <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Coro/" rel="nofollow">Coro</a>, <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/POE/" rel="nofollow">POE</a>) too, if that's what your app requires<br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; and the various Test::* modules, of course<br>
&lt;masak&gt; Hinrik: which ones, more exactly?<br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Test-Simple/" rel="nofollow">Test::More</a> usually works for me, along with some other specialized ones depending on the typo of app<br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; e.g. <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Test-Script/" rel="nofollow">Test::Script</a> to test if scripts compile<br>
&lt;Hinrik&gt; masak: oh, and <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Devel-Cover/" rel="nofollow">Devel::Cover</a> is also quite helpful in determining test coverage<br>
&lt;cfedde&gt; see also <a href="http://search.cpan.org/dist/Modern-Perl/" rel="nofollow">Modern::Perl</a> <br>
&lt;cfedde&gt; I think that the standard template will become 'use Modern::Perl; use Moose'
</code>

</p><p>Feel the need to add something to the list? The comments are open.</p></div>
	
    

	<div class="journalpage">
		
		<br>
		<a href="//use.perl.org/journal.pl?op=list&amp;uid=6289" class="all">List all Journal entries</a>
	</div>
</div>

